context: <a0_0><b5_0>Norfolk Island<b5_0/><a0_0/> is the only non-mainland Australian territory to have achieved self-governance. <a1_0><b6_0>The Norfolk Island Act 1979<b6_0/><a1_0/>, passed by the Parliament of Australia in 1979, is the Act under which the island was governed until the passing of <a2_0><b7_0>the Norfolk Island Legislation Amendment Act 2015<b7_0/><a2_0/>. The Australian government maintains authority on the island through an Administrator, currently <a3_0><b8_0>Gary Hardgrave<b8_0/><a3_0/>. From 1979 to 2015, a Legislative Assembly was elected by popular vote for terms of not more than <a4_0>three years<a4_0/>, although legislation passed by the Australian Parliament could extend its laws to the territory at will, including the power to override any laws made by the assembly.
